# Supermarket Billing System – Case Study (Compressed README)

## Overview

This project uses SQL to analyze supermarket data for better decisions in sales, inventory, discounts, and customer management.
It tracks customers, products, categories, sales, sale items, and discounts.

---

## Objectives

* Analyze customer spending patterns
* Track product sales and inventory
* Evaluate discounts and promotions
* Compare category-wise performance
* Find revenue trends and bottlenecks

---

## Tech & Tables

**Tech:** SQL
**Tables:** Customers_1, Products_1, Categories_1, Sales_1, SaleItems_1, Discounts_1

---

## Key Analysis

* Top customers = high-value customers
* Inactive customers (3 months no purchase) → target with offers
* Avg transaction value → segment customers
* Best-selling products → need frequent restocking
* Low-stock products → restock immediately
* Top categories → expand further
* Last 6 months vs previous 6 months sales → trend analysis
* Peak sales day → optimize staffing
* Discounts usually increase sales
* Poor discounted products → low demand, visibility, or season
* Unsold products (3 months) → remove or clear stock
* Food category performs best
* Weekend sales higher than weekdays

---

## Key Insights

* High-value customers drive revenue
* Some customers need re-engagement
* Fast-moving products need quick restocking
* Discounts boost sales volume
* Food category dominates
* Weekends are peak sales days

---

## Business Actions

* Loyalty programs for big spenders
* Re-engagement offers for inactive users
* Expand strong categories
* Improve inventory planning
* Weekend premium offers
* Weekday discount strategy

---

## Conclusion

SQL analysis converts raw supermarket data into useful insights to improve sales, inventory control, promotions, and customer satisfaction.
